{"title_page": "Sirras", "text_new": "{{Infobox monarch\n|name            = Sirras \n|title           =Children \n|image           =\n|caption         =\n|reign           = c. 423\u2013393 BC\n|coronation      =\n|full name       =\n|native_lang1     = [[Ancient Greek]]\n|native_lang1_name1 = \u03a3\u03af\u03c1\u03c1\u03b1\u03c2\n|predecessor     = \n|successor       = \n|queen           = A daughter of Arrhabaeus\n|spouse          =\n|issue           =\n|royal house     = \n|dynasty         =\n|father          = \n|mother          = \n|birth_date      = \n|birth_place     =\n|death_date      = After 390\n|death_place     = \n|date of burial  =\n|place of burial =\n|}}\n\n'''Sirras''' or '''Sirrhas''' ({{lang-grc|\u03a3\u03af\u03c1\u03c1\u03b1\u03c2}}; d. 390 BC) was a prince, royal member and perhaps [[prince-regent]] of [[Lynkestis]] (Lyncestis) in [[Upper Macedonia]] for his father-in-law King [[Arrhabaeus]] ({{floruit}} 423\u2013393 BC). He participated in the [[Pelopponesian War]] against [[Sparta]].\n\n==Life==\n\n===Origin===\nSirras's origin is disputed, scholars being divided on whether he was of [[Lynkestis|Lynkestian]] origin,<ref>{{harvnb|Hammond|1989|p=32}}; {{harvnb|Kapetanopoulos|1994|pp=9\u201314}}.</ref> of [[Illyria]]n origin or of Upper Macedonian origin with Illyrian ancestors.<ref>{{harvnb|Greenwalt|2010|p=286}}.</ref>\n\n===Pelopponesian War===\n{{main article|Battle of Lyncestis}}\n[[File:Pelop war en.png|thumb|Map of the Pelopponnesian War.]]\nSirras took part in the [[Pelopponesian War]] as an ally of [[Athens]], on the side of [[Arrhabaeus]] I of Lyncestis against [[Perdiccas]] of Macedonia.<ref>Cleopatras By John Edwin George Whitehorne{{page needed|date=July 2013}}</ref> In 423 BC Arrhabaeus threw off the Lower Macedonian yoke and became an ally of Sirras.<ref name=Ceka>{{cite book|title=The Illyrians to the Albanians|author=Neritan Ceka|year=2005}}{{page needed|date=July 2013}}</ref> This was reinforced when Sirras married the daughter of Arrhabaeus. At first [[Sparta]] avoided involvement in Macedon's war with Arrhabaeus, but in 423 BC they joined an expedition which ended with a retreat by the Macedonians and a brilliantly contrived escape of the Spartans.\n\nAfter an initial success against Arrhabaeus, Perdiccas persuaded his allies to await the arrival of Illyrian mercenaries. It has been claimed that the Illyrians were under the command of Sirras but this is not supported in historiography (Thucydides did not mention Sirras). Rather the Illyrians opted instead to join the army of Arrhabaeus as they were now allies.<ref>{{cite book|title=A Companion to Ancient Macedonia|author=Joseph Roisman, Ian Worthington|p=283}}</ref> The Spartan general, [[Brasidas]] who came to support the Macedonians in their advance into the remote regions of Lyncestis, was abandoned by the Macedonians but was able to extract his army of 4,000 from Illyrian encirclement.<ref>Hammond 1966{{page needed|date=July 2013}}</ref> [[Thucydides]] stated that the fear inspired by their warlike character made both Greek armies think it best to retreat. The young Spartans were clearly shaken by the fearsome appearance of the Illyrian forces.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Illyrians|author=John Wilkes|pages=117\u20138}}</ref>\n\nThucydides reports Brasidas saying that the Illyrians may terrify those with an active imagination, they are formidable in their outward bulk, their loud yelling is unbearable and the brandishing of their weapons in the air has a threatening appearance, but when it comes to real fighting with an opponent who stands his ground they are not what they seemed; they have no regular order that would make them ashamed of deserting their positions when hard pressed; with them flight and attack are equally honourable, and afford no test of courage; their independent mode of fighting never leaving anyone who wants to run away without a fair excuse of doing so.<ref>Thucydides. ''History of the Pelopponessian War'', 4.126.</ref>\n\nThucydides incidentally never makes any mention of Sirras. Basing himself on Aristotle's example of Sirras and Arrhabaeus,<ref>Aristot. Pol. 5.1311b | http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus:abo:tlg,0086,035:5:1311b</ref> N.G.L Hammond concludes that Sirras was a regent to the minor king Arrhabaeus,<ref>N.G.L.Hammond and G.T. Griffith, A History of Macedonia II, Oxford, 1979, 15 & 139, \"Rulers of Lyncus\"</ref> although Aristotle's quote can also be used to support the case that Sirras was a strategos and Arrhabaeus the king, as Kapetanopoulos argues.<ref>{{harvnb|Kapetanopoulos|1994|p=10}}.</ref>\n\n===War against Archelaus I of Macedon===\nAt the end of the 5th century BC, Sirras was once again at war with Macedonia over a claim on Lyncestis. Around the end of the reign of [[Archelaus I of Macedon]], ca. 400/399 BC, a new war developed between the two kings over Lyncestis. As in earlier times, Arrhabaeus and Sirras acted together. The results of this war are not known, but later events show that no change happened to the status quo.\n\n==Family==\nSirras' daughter, [[Eurydice I of Macedon|Eurydice]], married King [[Amyntas III of Macedon]] in around 390 BC, probably as part of an alliance against the [[Illyrians]],<ref>{{harvnb|Worthington|2008|p=15}}.</ref> after he suffered his first defeat by them in 393 BC.<ref name=\"Philip II\">{{cite web | author= | date = | title=Philip II of Macedonia| publisher=The Ancient World, Volume I |url=http://www.bookrags.com/tandf/philip-ii-of-macedonia-tf/ | accessdate=January 21, 2011}}</ref> One of the sons from this marriage was the future [[Philip II of Macedon]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|last=Greenwalt|first=William S.|chapter=Macedonia, Illyria, and Epirus|title=A Companion to Ancient Macedonia|pages=279\u2013305|location=Oxford, Chichester, & Malden|publisher=Wiley-Blackwell|year=2010|isbn=978-1-4051-7936-2|url=https://archive.org/stream/AncientMacedonia/Ancient%20Macedonia#page/n401/mode/2up|ref=harv|editor-given1=Joseph|editor-surname1=Roisman|editor-given2=Ian|editor-surname2=Worthington|}}\n*{{cite book|last=Hammond|first=Nicholas Geoffrey Lempri\u00e8re|title=The Macedonian State: Origins, Institutions, and History|location=Oxford|publisher=Clarendon Press|year=1989|isbn=0-19-814883-6|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4jRoAAAAMAAJ|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Kapetanopoulos|first=Elias|title=Sirras|journal=The Ancient World|year=1994|volume=XXV|number=1|url=http://web.ccsu.edu/elias/Sirras.pdf|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Worthington|first=Ian|year=2008|title=Phillip II of Macedonia|location=New Haven and London|publisher=Yale|isbn=978-0-300-12079-0|ref=harv}}\n\n[[Category:5th-century BC rulers]]\n[[Category:Ancient Macedonian generals]]\n[[Category:Ancient Lyncestians]]\n[[Category:Illyrian royalty]]\n[[Category:People of the Peloponnesian War]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox monarch\n|name            = Sirras \n|title           = \n|image           =\n|caption         =\n|reign           = c. 423\u2013393 BC\n|coronation      =\n|full name       =\n|native_lang1     = [[Ancient Greek]]\n|native_lang1_name1 = \u03a3\u03af\u03c1\u03c1\u03b1\u03c2\n|predecessor     = \n|successor       = \n|queen           = A daughter of Arrhabaeus\n|spouse          =\n|issue           =\n|royal house     = \n|dynasty         =\n|father          = \n|mother          = \n|birth_date      = \n|birth_place     =\n|death_date      = After 390\n|death_place     = \n|date of burial  =\n|place of burial =\n|}}\n\n'''Sirras''' or '''Sirrhas''' ({{lang-grc|\u03a3\u03af\u03c1\u03c1\u03b1\u03c2}}; d. 390 BC) was a prince, royal member and perhaps [[prince-regent]] of [[Lynkestis]] (Lyncestis) in [[Upper Macedonia]] for his father-in-law King [[Arrhabaeus]] ({{floruit}} 423\u2013393 BC). He participated in the [[Pelopponesian War]] against [[Sparta]].\n\n==Life==\n\n===Origin===\nSirras's origin is disputed, scholars being divided on whether he was of [[Lynkestis|Lynkestian]] origin,<ref>{{harvnb|Hammond|1989|p=32}}; {{harvnb|Kapetanopoulos|1994|pp=9\u201314}}.</ref> of [[Illyria]]n origin or of Upper Macedonian origin with Illyrian ancestors.<ref>{{harvnb|Greenwalt|2010|p=286}}.</ref>\n\n===Pelopponesian War===\n{{main article|Battle of Lyncestis}}\n[[File:Pelop war en.png|thumb|Map of the Pelopponnesian War.]]\nSirras took part in the [[Pelopponesian War]] as an ally of [[Athens]], on the side of [[Arrhabaeus]] I of Lyncestis against [[Perdiccas]] of Macedonia.<ref>Cleopatras By John Edwin George Whitehorne{{page needed|date=July 2013}}</ref> In 423 BC Arrhabaeus threw off the Lower Macedonian yoke and became an ally of Sirras.<ref name=Ceka>{{cite book|title=The Illyrians to the Albanians|author=Neritan Ceka|year=2005}}{{page needed|date=July 2013}}</ref> This was reinforced when Sirras married the daughter of Arrhabaeus. At first [[Sparta]] avoided involvement in Macedon's war with Arrhabaeus, but in 423 BC they joined an expedition which ended with a retreat by the Macedonians and a brilliantly contrived escape of the Spartans.\n\nAfter an initial success against Arrhabaeus, Perdiccas persuaded his allies to await the arrival of Illyrian mercenaries. It has been claimed that the Illyrians were under the command of Sirras but this is not supported in historiography (Thucydides did not mention Sirras). Rather the Illyrians opted instead to join the army of Arrhabaeus as they were now allies.<ref>{{cite book|title=A Companion to Ancient Macedonia|author=Joseph Roisman, Ian Worthington|p=283}}</ref> The Spartan general, [[Brasidas]] who came to support the Macedonians in their advance into the remote regions of Lyncestis, was abandoned by the Macedonians but was able to extract his army of 4,000 from Illyrian encirclement.<ref>Hammond 1966{{page needed|date=July 2013}}</ref> [[Thucydides]] stated that the fear inspired by their warlike character made both Greek armies think it best to retreat. The young Spartans were clearly shaken by the fearsome appearance of the Illyrian forces.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Illyrians|author=John Wilkes|pages=117\u20138}}</ref>\n\nThucydides reports Brasidas saying that the Illyrians may terrify those with an active imagination, they are formidable in their outward bulk, their loud yelling is unbearable and the brandishing of their weapons in the air has a threatening appearance, but when it comes to real fighting with an opponent who stands his ground they are not what they seemed; they have no regular order that would make them ashamed of deserting their positions when hard pressed; with them flight and attack are equally honourable, and afford no test of courage; their independent mode of fighting never leaving anyone who wants to run away without a fair excuse of doing so.<ref>Thucydides. ''History of the Pelopponessian War'', 4.126.</ref>\n\nThucydides incidentally never makes any mention of Sirras. Basing himself on Aristotle's example of Sirras and Arrhabaeus,<ref>Aristot. Pol. 5.1311b | http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus:abo:tlg,0086,035:5:1311b</ref> N.G.L Hammond concludes that Sirras was a regent to the minor king Arrhabaeus,<ref>N.G.L.Hammond and G.T. Griffith, A History of Macedonia II, Oxford, 1979, 15 & 139, \"Rulers of Lyncus\"</ref> although Aristotle's quote can also be used to support the case that Sirras was a strategos and Arrhabaeus the king, as Kapetanopoulos argues.<ref>{{harvnb|Kapetanopoulos|1994|p=10}}.</ref>\n\n===War against Archelaus I of Macedon===\nAt the end of the 5th century BC, Sirras was once again at war with Macedonia over a claim on Lyncestis. Around the end of the reign of [[Archelaus I of Macedon]], ca. 400/399 BC, a new war developed between the two kings over Lyncestis. As in earlier times, Arrhabaeus and Sirras acted together. The results of this war are not known, but later events show that no change happened to the status quo.\n\n==Family==\nSirras' daughter, [[Eurydice I of Macedon|Eurydice]], married King [[Amyntas III of Macedon]] in around 390 BC, probably as part of an alliance against the [[Illyrians]],<ref>{{harvnb|Worthington|2008|p=15}}.</ref> after he suffered his first defeat by them in 393 BC.<ref name=\"Philip II\">{{cite web | author= | date = | title=Philip II of Macedonia| publisher=The Ancient World, Volume I |url=http://www.bookrags.com/tandf/philip-ii-of-macedonia-tf/ | accessdate=January 21, 2011}}</ref> One of the sons from this marriage was the future [[Philip II of Macedon]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|last=Greenwalt|first=William S.|chapter=Macedonia, Illyria, and Epirus|title=A Companion to Ancient Macedonia|pages=279\u2013305|location=Oxford, Chichester, & Malden|publisher=Wiley-Blackwell|year=2010|isbn=978-1-4051-7936-2|url=https://archive.org/stream/AncientMacedonia/Ancient%20Macedonia#page/n401/mode/2up|ref=harv|editor-given1=Joseph|editor-surname1=Roisman|editor-given2=Ian|editor-surname2=Worthington|}}\n*{{cite book|last=Hammond|first=Nicholas Geoffrey Lempri\u00e8re|title=The Macedonian State: Origins, Institutions, and History|location=Oxford|publisher=Clarendon Press|year=1989|isbn=0-19-814883-6|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4jRoAAAAMAAJ|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Kapetanopoulos|first=Elias|title=Sirras|journal=The Ancient World|year=1994|volume=XXV|number=1|url=http://web.ccsu.edu/elias/Sirras.pdf|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Worthington|first=Ian|year=2008|title=Phillip II of Macedonia|location=New Haven and London|publisher=Yale|isbn=978-0-300-12079-0|ref=harv}}\n\n[[Category:5th-century BC rulers]]\n[[Category:Ancient Macedonian generals]]\n[[Category:Ancient Lyncestians]]\n[[Category:Illyrian royalty]]\n[[Category:People of the Peloponnesian War]]\n", "name_user": "Illyrianshqip", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sirras"}
